# CaptionDB Documentation Engineering Contract

## Purpose

This contract defines the documentation standards for CaptionDB.

Documentation is a required engineering deliverable.

No implementation is considered complete until its documentation is updated.

---

# Documentation Philosophy

Documentation should answer:

Why does this exist?

What problem does it solve?

How does it work?

How can it be extended?

Documentation should never become outdated.

Update documentation whenever implementation changes.

---

# Required Documentation

The repository must maintain:

README.md

PROJECT_SPEC.md

ARCHITECTURE.md

API_SPEC.md

BACKEND_SPEC.md

FRONTEND_SPEC.md

SECURITY_SPEC.md

PERFORMANCE_SPEC.md

TESTING_SPEC.md

DOCKER_SPEC.md

DEVELOPMENT.md

CHANGELOG.md

DECISION_LOG.md

---

# README

README is the public entry point.

It must include:

Project Overview

Features

Architecture

Technology Stack

Installation

Quick Start

Configuration

Docker Usage

Running Tests

Repository Structure

License

Contributing

Future Roadmap

README should always reflect the latest project state.

---

# Architecture Documentation

Architecture documentation should explain:

System Overview

Component Relationships

Data Flow

Pipeline

Module Responsibilities

Dependency Flow

Future Extensions

Architecture diagrams should remain consistent with implementation.

---

# API Documentation

Every endpoint must include:

Purpose

Request Schema

Response Schema

Status Codes

Error Responses

Authentication (future)

Example Requests

Example Responses

FastAPI OpenAPI documentation should remain complete.

---

# Backend Documentation

Every backend module should document:

Purpose

Dependencies

Inputs

Outputs

Failure Modes

Configuration

Extension Points

---

# Frontend Documentation

Document:

Pages

Components

Hooks

Contexts

API Services

State Management

Routing

User Flows

---

# AI Pipeline Documentation

Every stage must document:

Purpose

Input

Output

Dependencies

Configuration

Failure Recovery

Metrics

Examples

---

# Configuration Documentation

Document every configuration option.

Include:

Name

Purpose

Type

Default

Required

Example

Never leave undocumented configuration.

---

# Code Documentation

Every public:

Class

Function

Method

Module

must contain:

Description

Parameters

Returns

Raises

Examples (when appropriate)

Use Google-style docstrings.

---

# Inline Comments

Comments should explain WHY.

Avoid comments explaining obvious code.

Prefer self-documenting code.

---

# Decision Log

Maintain a DECISION_LOG.md.

Every significant engineering decision should record:

Date

Decision

Reason

Alternatives Considered

Tradeoffs

Expected Impact

This prevents future confusion.

---

# Changelog

Maintain CHANGELOG.md.

Document:

Added

Changed

Fixed

Removed

Deprecated

Released

Never overwrite previous entries.

---

# Development Log

Maintain DEVELOPMENT.md.

Track:

Current Milestone

Completed Tasks

Pending Tasks

Known Issues

Future Work

Repository Status

---

# Versioning

Documentation should include version numbers where appropriate.

Example:

v1.0

v1.1

v2.0

Avoid undocumented changes.

---

# Diagrams

Prefer diagrams for:

Architecture

Pipeline

Data Flow

Module Interaction

Deployment

Keep diagrams synchronized with implementation.

---

# Examples

Provide examples whenever practical.

Examples should be:

Complete

Runnable

Up-to-date

Verified

---

# Error Documentation

Document:

Possible failures

Recovery actions

Known limitations

Common troubleshooting steps

Avoid undocumented behavior.

---

# Dependencies

Document every major dependency.

Include:

Purpose

Version

Official Documentation

Reason for Selection

Alternatives

---

# Security Documentation

Document:

Security assumptions

Input validation

Secrets management

Authentication roadmap

Threat considerations

Do not expose sensitive implementation details.

---

# Performance Documentation

Document:

Caching

Parallelism

Memory optimization

Resource limits

Benchmarks

Performance assumptions

---

# Docker Documentation

Document:

Build

Run

Environment Variables

Volumes

Ports

Health Checks

Troubleshooting

---

# Testing Documentation

Document:

Testing strategy

Test structure

How to run tests

Coverage expectations

Mock strategy

Sample test commands

---

# Prompt Documentation

Prompt templates should include:

Purpose

Version

Expected Inputs

Expected Outputs

Supported Models

Notes

Never leave prompt behavior undocumented.

---

# Repository Consistency

Every new folder should contain documentation if its purpose is not immediately obvious.

Avoid undocumented directories.

---

# Documentation Quality

Documentation should be:

Accurate

Complete

Concise

Professional

Consistent

Avoid outdated examples.

---

# Documentation Review

Whenever code changes:

Review affected documentation.

Update examples.

Update diagrams if necessary.

Update changelog.

Update decision log if architecture changes.

---

# Documentation Checklist

Before completing implementation verify:

✓ README updated if required

✓ API documentation updated

✓ Architecture documentation updated

✓ Code docstrings added

✓ Configuration documented

✓ Decision log updated

✓ Changelog updated

✓ Development log updated

✓ Examples verified

✓ Diagrams reviewed

✓ Documentation consistent with implementation

If any item fails, revise documentation before considering the implementation complete.

---

End of Documentation Engineering Contract.
